<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-163-508  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 163 508.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Feb 19 1990 n455 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fed export proposal decried. (proposed regulations on high-endcomputers)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nee, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer manufacturers are raising a strong protest against the USDepartment of Commerce's (DOC) proposed export regulationscovering computers capable of performing over 100-MFLOPS.andO;Previously, export permission has been granted on a case by casebasis, but Congress wants a definition of what a supercomputer isin order to regulate their availability.andP;  Under the proposedregulation, machines capable of more than 300-MFLOPS can only besold to 23 favored nations, and then only with safeguardsregarding their potential use.andP;  Computers capable of between 150and 300-MFLOPS would be available to other non-communistcountries.andP;  Manufacturers like IBM claim the threshold is too lowand that it will 'absolutely' curtail overseas sales of IBMmainframes.andP;  Others point to the fact that Intel already producesa chip for microcomputers that performs 60-MFLOPS.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of CommerceGovernment RegulationExportInternational TradeSupercomputersComputer Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>